[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In numerical optimization, the **Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno** (**BFGS**) **algorithm** is an iterative method for solving unconstrained nonlinear optimization problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Like the related Davidon–Fletcher–Powell method, BFGS determines the descent direction by preconditioning the gradient with curvature information.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] It does so by gradually improving an approximation to the Hessian matrix of the loss function, obtained only from gradient evaluations (or approximate gradient evaluations) via a generalized secant method.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Since the updates of the BFGS curvature matrix do not require matrix inversion, its computational complexity is only ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ , compared to ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ in Newton's method.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Also in common use is L-BFGS, which is a limited-memory version of BFGS that is particularly suited to problems with very large numbers of variables (e.g., >1000).
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The BFGS-B variant handles simple box constraints.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The BFGS matrix also admits a compact representation, which makes it better suited for large constrained problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The algorithm is named after Charles George Broyden, Roger Fletcher, Donald Goldfarb and David Shanno.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] It is an instance of a more general algorithm by John Greenstadt.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The optimization problem is to minimize $f(\mathbf {x} )$ , where $\mathbf {x}$ is a vector in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , and f is a differentiable scalar function.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] There are no constraints on the values that $\mathbf {x}$ can take.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The algorithm begins at an initial estimate $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ for the optimal value and proceeds iteratively to get a better estimate at each stage.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] where $B_{k}$ is an approximation to the Hessian matrix at $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ , which is updated iteratively at each stage, and $\nabla f(\mathbf {x} _{k})$ is the gradient of the function evaluated at **x***k*.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The curvature condition $\mathbf {s} _{k}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {y} _{k}>0$ should be satisfied for $B_{k+1}$ to be positive definite, which can be verified by pre-multiplying the secant equation with $\mathbf {s} _{k}^{\mathsf {T}}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] If the function is not strongly convex, then the condition has to be enforced explicitly e.g. by finding a point **x***k*+1 satisfying the Wolfe conditions, which entail the curvature condition, using line search.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Both $U_{k}$ and $V_{k}$ are symmetric rank-one matrices, but their sum is a rank-two update matrix.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] BFGS and DFP updating matrix both differ from its predecessor by a rank-two matrix.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Another simpler rank-one method is known as symmetric rank-one method, which does not guarantee the positive definiteness.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In order to maintain the symmetry and positive definiteness of $B_{k+1}$ , the update form can be chosen as $B_{k+1}=B_{k}+\alpha \mathbf {u} \mathbf {u} ^{\mathsf {T}}+\beta \mathbf {v} \mathbf {v} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Consider the following unconstrained optimization problem ${\begin{aligned}{\underset {\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{n}}{\text{minimize}}}\quad &f(\mathbf {x} ),\end{aligned}}$ where $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ is a nonlinear, twice-differentiable objective function.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Perform a one-dimensional optimization (line search) to find an acceptable stepsize $\alpha _{k}$ in the direction found in the first step.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] If an exact line search is performed, then $\alpha _{k}=\arg \min _{\alpha }f(\mathbf {x} _{k}+\alpha \mathbf {p} _{k})$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In practice, an inexact line search usually suffices, with an acceptable $\alpha _{k}$ satisfying Wolfe conditions.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In statistical estimation problems (such as maximum likelihood or Bayesian inference), credible intervals or confidence intervals for the solution can be estimated from the inverse of the final Hessian matrix .
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] However, these quantities are technically defined by the true Hessian matrix, and the BFGS approximation may not converge to the true Hessian matrix.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The BFGS update formula heavily relies on the curvature $\mathbf {s} _{k}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {y} _{k}$ being strictly positive and bounded away from zero.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] This condition is satisfied when we perform a line search with Wolfe conditions on a convex target.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] However, some real-life applications (like Sequential Quadratic Programming methods) routinely produce negative or nearly-zero curvatures.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] This can occur when optimizing a nonconvex target or when employing a trust-region approach instead of a line search.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] It is also possible to produce spurious values due to noise in the target.
[src:optimization-scipy/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In such cases, one of the so-called damped BFGS updates can be used (see ) which modify $\mathbf {s} _{k}$ and/or $\mathbf {y} _{k}$ in order to obtain a more robust update.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The idea is to take repeated steps in the opposite direction of the gradient (or approximate gradient) of the function at the current point, because this is the direction of steepest descent.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Conversely, stepping in the direction of the gradient will lead to a trajectory that maximizes that function; the procedure is then known as *gradient ascent*.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent should not be confused with local search algorithms, although both are iterative methods for optimization.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is particularly useful in machine learning and artificial intelligence for minimizing the cost or loss function.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is generally attributed to Augustin-Louis Cauchy, who first suggested it in 1847.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Jacques Hadamard independently proposed a similar method in 1907.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Its convergence properties for non-linear optimization problems were first studied by Haskell Curry in 1944, with the method becoming increasingly well-studied and used in the following decades.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] A simple extension of gradient descent, stochastic gradient descent, serves as the most basic algorithm used for training most deep networks today.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] for a small enough step size or learning rate $\eta \in \mathbb {R} _{+}$ , then $f(\mathbf {a_{n}} )\geq f(\mathbf {a_{n+1}} )$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] In other words, the term $\eta \nabla f(\mathbf {a} )$ is subtracted from $\mathbf {a}$ because we want to move against the gradient, toward the local minimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] so the sequence $(\mathbf {x} _{n})$ converges to the desired local minimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Note that the value of the *step size* $\eta$ is allowed to change at every iteration.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] It is possible to guarantee the convergence to a local minimum under certain assumptions on the function f (for example, f convex and $\nabla f$ Lipschitz) and particular choices of $\eta$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] as in the Barzilai-Borwein method, or a sequence $\eta _{n}$ satisfying the Wolfe conditions (which can be found by using line search).
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] When the function f is convex, all local minima are also global minima, so in this case gradient descent can converge to the global solution.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] This process is illustrated in the adjacent picture.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Here, f is assumed to be defined on the plane, and that its graph has a bowl shape.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The blue curves are the contour lines, that is, the regions on which the value of f is constant.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] A red arrow originating at a point shows the direction of the negative gradient at that point.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Note that the (negative) gradient at a point is orthogonal to the contour line going through that point.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] We see that gradient *descent* leads us to the bottom of the bowl, that is, to the point where the value of the function f is minimal.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The basic intuition behind gradient descent can be illustrated by a hypothetical scenario.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] People are stuck in the mountains and are trying to get down (i.e., trying to find the global minimum).
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] There is heavy fog such that visibility is extremely low.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Therefore, the path down the mountain is not visible, so they must use local information to find the minimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] They can use the method of gradient descent, which involves looking at the steepness of the hill at their current position, then proceeding in the direction with the steepest descent (i.e., downhill).
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] If they were trying to find the top of the mountain (i.e., the maximum), then they would proceed in the direction of steepest ascent (i.e., uphill).
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Using this method, they would eventually find their way down the mountain or possibly get stuck in some hole (i.e., local minimum or saddle point), like a mountain lake.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] However, assume also that the steepness of the hill is not immediately obvious with simple observation, but rather it requires a sophisticated instrument to measure, which the people happen to have at that moment.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] It takes quite some time to measure the steepness of the hill with the instrument.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Thus, they should minimize their use of the instrument if they want to get down the mountain before sunset.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The difficulty then is choosing the frequency at which they should measure the steepness of the hill so as not to go off track.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] In this analogy, the people represent the algorithm, and the path taken down the mountain represents the sequence of parameter settings that the algorithm will explore.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The steepness of the hill represents the slope of the function at that point.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The instrument used to measure steepness is differentiation.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The direction they choose to travel in aligns with the gradient of the function at that point.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The amount of time they travel before taking another measurement is the step size.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Since using a step size $\eta$ that is too small would slow convergence, and a $\eta$ too large would lead to overshoot and divergence, finding a good setting of $\eta$ is an important practical problem.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Philip Wolfe also advocated using "clever choices of the [descent] direction" in practice.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] While using a direction that deviates from the steepest descent direction may seem counter-intuitive, the idea is that the smaller slope may be compensated for by being sustained over a much longer distance.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Finding good settings of $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ and $\eta _{n}$ requires some thought.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] First of all, we would like the update direction to point downhill.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Mathematically, letting $\theta _{n}$ denote the angle between $-\nabla f(\mathbf {a_{n}} )$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ , this requires that $\cos \theta _{n}>0.$ To say more, we need more information about the objective function that we are optimising.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] This inequality implies that the amount by which we can be sure the function f is decreased depends on a trade off between the two terms in square brackets.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The first term in square brackets measures the angle between the descent direction and the negative gradient.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The second term measures how quickly the gradient changes along the descent direction.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] In principle inequality (**1**) could be optimized over $\mathbf {p} _{n}$ and $\eta _{n}$ to choose an optimal step size and direction.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The problem is that evaluating the second term in square brackets requires evaluating $\nabla f(\mathbf {a} _{n}-t\eta _{n}\mathbf {p} _{n})$ , and extra gradient evaluations are generally expensive and undesirable.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Usually by following one of the recipes above, convergence to a local minimum can be guaranteed.
