[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The method is rarely used for solving linear equations, with the conjugate gradient method being one of the most popular alternatives.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Both methods can benefit from preconditioning, where gradient descent may require less assumptions on the preconditioner.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Because each step is taken in the steepest direction, steepest-descent steps alternate between directions aligned with the extreme axes of the elongated level sets.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] When $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ is large, this produces a characteristic zig–zag path.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The poor conditioning of $\mathbf {A}$ is the primary cause of the slow convergence, and orthogonality of successive residuals reinforces this alternation.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] As shown in the image on the right, steepest descent converges slowly due to the high condition number of $\mathbf {A}$ , and the orthogonality of residuals forces each new direction to undo the overshoot from the previous step.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The result is a path that zigzags toward the solution.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] This inefficiency is one reason conjugate gradient or preconditioning methods are preferred.
