[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent works in spaces of any number of dimensions, even in infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] In the latter case, the search space is typically a function space, and one calculates the Fréchet derivative of the functional to be minimized to determine the descent direction.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] That gradient descent works in any number of dimensions (finite number at least) can be seen as a consequence of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, i.e. the magnitude of the inner (dot) product of two vectors of any dimension is maximized when they are colinear.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] In the case of gradient descent, that would be when the vector of independent variable adjustments is proportional to the gradient vector of partial derivatives.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can take many iterations to compute a local minimum with a required accuracy, if the curvature in different directions is very different for the given function.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] For such functions, preconditioning, which changes the geometry of the space to shape the function level sets like concentric circles, cures the slow convergence.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Constructing and applying preconditioning can be computationally expensive, however.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The gradient descent can be modified via momentums (Nesterov, Polyak, and Frank–Wolfe) and heavy-ball parameters (exponential moving averages and positive-negative momentum).
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The main examples of such optimizers are Adam, DiffGrad, Yogi, AdaBelief, etc.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Methods based on Newton's method and inversion of the Hessian using conjugate gradient techniques can be better alternatives.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Generally, such methods converge in fewer iterations, but the cost of each iteration is higher.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] While it is sometimes possible to substitute gradient descent for a local search algorithm, gradient descent is not in the same family: although it is an iterative method for local optimization, it relies on an objective function's gradient rather than an explicit exploration of a solution space.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be viewed as applying Euler's method for solving ordinary differential equations $x'(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ to a gradient flow.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] In turn, this equation may be derived as an optimal controller for the control system $x'(t)=u(t)$ with $u(t)$ given in feedback form $u(t)=-\nabla f(x(t))$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can converge to a local minimum and slow down in a neighborhood of a saddle point.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Even for unconstrained quadratic minimization, gradient descent develops a zig–zag pattern of subsequent iterates as iterations progress, resulting in slow convergence.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Multiple modifications of gradient descent have been proposed to address these deficiencies.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Yurii Nesterov has proposed a simple modification that enables faster convergence for convex problems and has been since further generalized.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] For unconstrained smooth problems, the method is called the fast gradient method (FGM) or the accelerated gradient method (AGM).
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Specifically, if the differentiable function f is convex and $\nabla f$ is Lipschitz, and it is not assumed that f is strongly convex, then the error in the objective value generated at each step k by the gradient descent method will be bounded by ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-1}}\right)}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Using the Nesterov acceleration technique, the error decreases at ${\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] It is known that the rate ${\mathcal {O}}\left({k^{-2}}\right)$ for the decrease of the cost function is optimal for first-order optimization methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Nevertheless, there is the opportunity to improve the algorithm by reducing the constant factor.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The optimized gradient method (OGM) reduces that constant by a factor of two and is an optimal first-order method for large-scale problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] For constrained or non-smooth problems, Nesterov's FGM is called the fast proximal gradient method (FPGM), an acceleration of the proximal gradient method.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent with momentum remembers the solution update at each iteration, and determines the next update as a linear combination of the gradient and the previous update.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] For unconstrained quadratic minimization, a theoretical convergence rate bound of the heavy ball method is asymptotically the same as that for the optimal conjugate gradient method.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] This technique is used in stochastic gradient descent and as an extension to the backpropagation algorithms used to train artificial neural networks.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] In the direction of updating, stochastic gradient descent adds a stochastic property.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The weights can be used to calculate the derivatives.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent can be extended to handle constraints by including a projection onto the set of constraints.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] This method is only feasible when the projection is efficiently computable on a computer.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Under suitable assumptions, this method converges.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] This method is a specific case of the forward–backward algorithm for monotone inclusions (which includes convex programming and variational inequalities).
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Gradient descent is a special case of mirror descent using the squared Euclidean distance as the given Bregman divergence.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The properties of gradient descent depend on the properties of the objective function and the variant of gradient descent used (for example, if a line search step is used).
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] The assumptions made affect the convergence rate, and other properties, that can be proven for gradient descent.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] For example, if the objective is assumed to be strongly convex and lipschitz smooth, then gradient descent converges linearly with a fixed step size.
[src:optimization-scipy/gradient-descent] Looser assumptions lead to either weaker convergence guarantees or require a more sophisticated step size selection.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] In contrast to active-set methods (such as the simplex method) which traverses the *boundary* of the feasible region, and the ellipsoid method which bounds the feasible region from *outside*, an IPM reaches a best solution by traversing the *interior* of the feasible region—hence the name.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] An interior point method was discovered by Soviet mathematician I.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] The method was reinvented in the U.S. in the mid-1980s.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] In 1984, Narendra Karmarkar developed a method for linear programming called Karmarkar's algorithm, which runs in polynomial time ( $O(n^{3.5}L)$ operations on *L*-bit numbers, where *n* is the number of variables and constants), and is also very efficient in practice.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Karmarkar's paper created a surge of interest in interior point methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Two years later, James Renegar invented the first *path-following* interior-point method, with run-time $O(n^{3}L)$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] The method was later extended from linear to convex optimization problems, based on a self-concordant barrier function used to encode the convex set.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Any convex optimization problem can be transformed into minimizing (or maximizing) a linear function over a convex set by converting to the epigraph form.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] The idea of encoding the feasible set using a barrier and designing barrier methods was studied by Anthony V.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] McCormick, and others in the early 1960s.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] These ideas were mainly developed for general nonlinear programming, but they were later abandoned due to the presence of more competitive methods for this class of problems (e.g. sequential quadratic programming).
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Yurii Nesterov and Arkadi Nemirovski came up with a special class of such barriers that can be used to encode any convex set.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] They guarantee that the number of iterations of the algorithm is bounded by a polynomial in the dimension and accuracy of the solution.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] The class of primal-dual path-following interior-point methods is considered the most successful.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Mehrotra's predictor–corrector algorithm provides the basis for most implementations of this class of methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] We are given a convex program of the form: ${\begin{aligned}{\underset {x\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}}{\text{minimize}}}\quad &f(x)\\{\text{subject to}}\quad &x\in G.\end{aligned}}$ where f is a convex function and G is a convex set.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Without loss of generality, we can assume that the objective *f* is a linear function.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] The dimension of this coefficient vector is called the *size* of the program.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] A *numerical solver* for a given family of programs is an algorithm that, given the coefficient vector, generates a sequence of approximate solutions *xt* for *t*=1,2,..., using finitely many arithmetic operations.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] where *V* is some data-dependent constant, e.g., the difference between the largest and smallest value in the feasible set.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] In other words, *V*/*ε* is the "relative accuracy" of the solution - the accuracy w.r.t. the largest coefficient. log(*V*/*ε*) represents the number of "accuracy digits".
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Therefore, a solver is 'polynomial' if each additional digit of accuracy requires a number of operations that is polynomial in the problem size.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Given a convex optimization program (P) with constraints, we can convert it to an *unconstrained* program by adding a barrier function.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Specifically, let *b* be a smooth convex function, defined in the interior of the feasible region *G*, such that for any sequence $\{x_{j}\in {\textbf {G}}\}$ whose limit is on the boundary of *G*: $\lim _{j\to \infty }b(x_{j})=\infty$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] We also assume that *b* is non-degenerate, that is: $b''(x)$ is positive definite for all x in interior(G).
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Technically the program is restricted, since *b* is defined only in the interior of *G*.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] But practically, it is possible to solve it as an unconstrained program, since any solver trying to minimize the function will not approach the boundary, where *b* approaches infinity.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] Therefore, (*Pt*) has a unique solution - denote it by *x**(*t*).
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] The function *x** is a continuous function of *t*, which is called the *central path*.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] All limit points of *x**, as *t* approaches infinity, are optimal solutions of the original program (P).
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] The main challenge in proving that the method is polytime is that, as the penalty parameter grows, the solution gets near the boundary, and the function becomes steeper.
[src:optimization-scipy/interior-point-method] The run-time of solvers such as Newton's method becomes longer, and it is hard to prove that the total runtime is polynomial.
