[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In the more general approach, an optimization problem consists of maximizing or minimizing a real function by systematically choosing input values from within an allowed set and computing the value of the function.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The generalization of optimization theory and techniques to other formulations constitutes a large area of applied mathematics.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Such a formulation is called an **optimization problem** or a **mathematical programming problem** (a term not directly related to computer programming, but still in use for example in linear programming – see History below).
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Many real-world and theoretical problems may be modeled in this general framework.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] it suffices to solve only minimization problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] However, the opposite perspective of considering only maximization problems would be valid, too.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Problems formulated using this technique in the fields of physics may refer to the technique as *energy minimization*, speaking of the value of the function f as representing the energy of the system being modeled.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In machine learning, it is always necessary to continuously evaluate the quality of a data model by using a cost function where a minimum implies a set of possibly optimal parameters with an optimal (lowest) error.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Typically, A is some subset of the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , often specified by a set of *constraints*, equalities or inequalities that the members of A have to satisfy.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The domain A of f is called the *search space* or the *choice set*, while the elements of A are called *candidate solutions* or *feasible solutions*.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The function f is variously called an *objective function*, *criterion function*, *loss function*, *cost function* (minimization), *utility function* or *fitness function* (maximization), or, in certain fields, an *energy function* or *energy functional*.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] A feasible solution that minimizes (or maximizes) the objective function is called an *optimal solution*.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In mathematics, conventional optimization problems are usually stated in terms of minimization.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] that is to say, on some region around **x*** all of the function values are greater than or equal to the value at that element.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] While a local minimum is at least as good as any nearby elements, a global minimum is at least as good as every feasible element.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Generally, unless the objective function is convex in a minimization problem, there may be several local minima.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In a convex problem, if there is a local minimum that is interior (not on the edge of the set of feasible elements), it is also the global minimum, but a nonconvex problem may have more than one local minimum not all of which need be global minima.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Global optimization is the branch of applied mathematics and numerical analysis that is concerned with the development of deterministic algorithms that are capable of guaranteeing convergence in finite time to the actual optimal solution of a nonconvex problem.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Optimization problems are often expressed with special notation.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] This denotes the minimum value of the objective function *x*2 + 1, when choosing x from the set of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The minimum value in this case is 1, occurring at *x* = 0.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] asks for the maximum value of the objective function 2*x*, where x may be any real number.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In this case, there is no such maximum as the objective function is unbounded, so the answer is "infinity" or "undefined".
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] This represents the value (or values) of the argument x in the interval (−∞,−1] that minimizes (or minimize) the objective function *x*2 + 1 (the actual minimum value of that function is not what the problem asks for).
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In this case, the answer is *x* = −1, since *x* = 0 is infeasible, that is, it does not belong to the feasible set.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] represents the {*x*, *y*} pair (or pairs) that maximizes (or maximize) the value of the objective function *x* cos *y*, with the added constraint that x lie in the interval [−5,5] (again, the actual maximum value of the expression does not matter).
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In this case, the solutions are the pairs of the form {5, 2*k*π} and {−5, (2*k* + 1)π}, where k ranges over all integers.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Operators arg min and arg max are sometimes also written as argmin and argmax, and stand for *argument of the minimum* and *argument of the maximum*.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Fermat and Lagrange found calculus-based formulae for identifying optima, while Newton and Gauss proposed iterative methods for moving towards an optimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The term "linear programming" for certain optimization cases was due to George B.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Dantzig, although much of the theory had been introduced by Leonid Kantorovich in 1939.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Adding more than one objective to an optimization problem adds complexity.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] For example, to optimize a structural design, one would desire a design that is both light and rigid.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] When two objectives conflict, a trade-off must be created.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] There may be one lightest design, one stiffest design, and an infinite number of designs that are some compromise of weight and rigidity.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The set of trade-off designs that improve upon one criterion at the expense of another is known as the Pareto set.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The curve created plotting weight against stiffness of the best designs is known as the Pareto frontier.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] A design is judged to be "Pareto optimal" (equivalently, "Pareto efficient" or in the Pareto set) if it is not dominated by any other design: If it is worse than another design in some respects and no better in any respect, then it is dominated and is not Pareto optimal.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The choice among "Pareto optimal" solutions to determine the "favorite solution" is delegated to the decision maker.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In other words, defining the problem as multi-objective optimization signals that some information is missing: desirable objectives are given but combinations of them are not rated relative to each other.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In some cases, the missing information can be derived by interactive sessions with the decision maker.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Multi-objective optimization problems have been generalized further into vector optimization problems where the (partial) ordering is no longer given by the Pareto ordering.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Optimization problems are often multi-modal; that is, they possess multiple good solutions.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] They could all be globally good (same cost function value) or there could be a mix of globally good and locally good solutions.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Obtaining all (or at least some of) the multiple solutions is the goal of a multi-modal optimizer.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Classical optimization techniques due to their iterative approach do not perform satisfactorily when they are used to obtain multiple solutions, since it is not guaranteed that different solutions will be obtained even with different starting points in multiple runs of the algorithm.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Common approaches to global optimization problems, where multiple local extrema may be present include evolutionary algorithms, Bayesian optimization and simulated annealing.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The *satisfiability problem*, also called the *feasibility problem*, is just the problem of finding any feasible solution at all without regard to objective value.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] This can be regarded as the special case of mathematical optimization where the objective value is the same for every solution, and thus any solution is optimal.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Many optimization algorithms need to start from a feasible point.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] One way to obtain such a point is to relax the feasibility conditions using a slack variable; with enough slack, any starting point is feasible.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Then, minimize that slack variable until the slack is null or negative.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The extreme value theorem of Karl Weierstrass states that a continuous real-valued function on a compact set attains its maximum and minimum value.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] More generally, a lower semi-continuous function on a compact set attains its minimum; an upper semi-continuous function on a compact set attains its maximum point or view.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] One of Fermat's theorems states that optima of unconstrained problems are found at stationary points, where the first derivative or the gradient of the objective function is zero (see first derivative test).
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] More generally, they may be found at critical points, where the first derivative or gradient of the objective function is zero or is undefined, or on the boundary of the choice set.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] An equation (or set of equations) stating that the first derivative(s) equal(s) zero at an interior optimum is called a 'first-order condition' or a set of first-order conditions.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Optima of equality-constrained problems can be found by the Lagrange multiplier method.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The optima of problems with equality and/or inequality constraints can be found using the 'Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions'.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] While the first derivative test identifies points that might be extrema, this test does not distinguish a point that is a minimum from one that is a maximum or one that is neither.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The conditions that distinguish maxima, or minima, from other stationary points are called 'second-order conditions' (see 'Second derivative test').
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] If a candidate solution satisfies the first-order conditions, then the satisfaction of the second-order conditions as well is sufficient to establish at least local optimality.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The envelope theorem describes how the value of an optimal solution changes when an underlying parameter changes.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The process of computing this change is called comparative statics.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The maximum theorem of Claude Berge (1963) describes the continuity of an optimal solution as a function of underlying parameters.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] For unconstrained problems with twice-differentiable functions, some critical points can be found by finding the points where the gradient of the objective function is zero (that is, the stationary points).
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] More generally, a zero subgradient certifies that a local minimum has been found for minimization problems with convex functions and other locally Lipschitz functions, which meet in loss function minimization of the neural network.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The positive-negative momentum estimation lets to avoid the local minimum and converges at the objective function global minimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Constrained problems can often be transformed into unconstrained problems with the help of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Lagrangian relaxation can also provide approximate solutions to difficult constrained problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] When the objective function is a convex function, then any local minimum will also be a global minimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] There exist efficient numerical techniques for minimizing convex functions, such as interior-point methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] More generally, if the objective function is not a quadratic function, then many optimization methods use other methods to ensure that some subsequence of iterations converges to an optimal solution.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The first and still popular method for ensuring convergence relies on line searches, which optimize a function along one dimension.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] A second and increasingly popular method for ensuring convergence uses trust regions.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Both line searches and trust regions are used in modern methods of non-differentiable optimization.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Usually, a global optimizer is much slower than advanced local optimizers (such as BFGS), so often an efficient global optimizer can be constructed by starting the local optimizer from different starting points.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] To solve problems, researchers may use algorithms that terminate in a finite number of steps, or iterative methods that converge to a solution (on some specified class of problems), or heuristics that may provide approximate solutions to some problems (although their iterates need not converge).
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The iterative methods used to solve problems of nonlinear programming differ according to whether they evaluate Hessians, gradients, or only function values.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] While evaluating Hessians (H) and gradients (G) improves the rate of convergence, for functions for which these quantities exist and vary sufficiently smoothly, such evaluations increase the computational complexity (or computational cost) of each iteration.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In some cases, the computational complexity may be excessively high.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] One major criterion for optimizers is just the number of required function evaluations as this often is already a large computational effort, usually much more effort than within the optimizer itself, which mainly has to operate over the N variables.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The derivatives provide detailed information for such optimizers, but are even harder to calculate, e.g. approximating the gradient takes at least N+1 function evaluations.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] For approximations of the 2nd derivatives (collected in the Hessian matrix), the number of function evaluations is in the order of N².
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Newton's method requires the 2nd-order derivatives, so for each iteration, the number of function calls is in the order of N², but for a simpler pure gradient optimizer it is only N.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] However, gradient optimizers need usually more iterations than Newton's algorithm.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Which one is best with respect to the number of function calls depends on the problem itself.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Besides (finitely terminating) algorithms and (convergent) iterative methods, there are heuristics.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] A heuristic is any algorithm which is not guaranteed (mathematically) to find the solution, but which is nevertheless useful in certain practical situations.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Also, the problem of computing contact forces can be done by solving a linear complementarity problem, which can also be viewed as a QP (quadratic programming) problem.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Many design problems can also be expressed as optimization programs.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] This application is called design optimization.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] One subset is the engineering optimization, and another recent and growing subset of this field is multidisciplinary design optimization, which, while useful in many problems, has in particular been applied to aerospace engineering problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] This approach may be applied in cosmology and astrophysics.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Economics is closely enough linked to optimization of agents that an influential definition relatedly describes economics *qua* science as the "study of human behavior as a relationship between ends and scarce means" with alternative uses.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Modern optimization theory includes traditional optimization theory but also overlaps with game theory and the study of economic equilibria.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The *Journal of Economic Literature* codes classify mathematical programming, optimization techniques, and related topics under JEL:C61-C63.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] In microeconomics, the utility maximization problem and its dual problem, the expenditure minimization problem, are economic optimization problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Insofar as they behave consistently, consumers are assumed to maximize their utility, while firms are usually assumed to maximize their profit.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Also, agents are often modeled as being risk-averse, thereby preferring to avoid risk.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Asset prices are also modeled using optimization theory, though the underlying mathematics relies on optimizing stochastic processes rather than on static optimization.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] International trade theory also uses optimization to explain trade patterns between nations.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The optimization of portfolios is an example of multi-objective optimization in economics.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Since the 1970s, economists have modeled dynamic decisions over time using control theory.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] For example, dynamic search models are used to study labor-market behavior.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] A crucial distinction is between deterministic and stochastic models.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Macroeconomists build dynamic stochastic general equilibrium (DSGE) models that describe the dynamics of the whole economy as the result of the interdependent optimizing decisions of workers, consumers, investors, and governments.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Some common applications of optimization techniques in electrical engineering include active filter design, stray field reduction in superconducting magnetic energy storage systems, space mapping design of microwave structures, handset antennas, electromagnetics-based design.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Electromagnetically validated design optimization of microwave components and antennas has made extensive use of an appropriate physics-based or empirical surrogate model and space mapping methodologies since the discovery of space mapping in 1993.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are also used in power-flow analysis.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Optimization has been widely used in civil engineering.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Construction management and transportation engineering are among the main branches of civil engineering that heavily rely on optimization.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The most common civil engineering problems that are solved by optimization are cut and fill of roads, life-cycle analysis of structures and infrastructures, resource leveling, water resource allocation, traffic management and schedule optimization.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Another field that uses optimization techniques extensively is operations research.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Operations research also uses stochastic modeling and simulation to support improved decision-making.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Increasingly, operations research uses stochastic programming to model dynamic decisions that adapt to events; such problems can be solved with large-scale optimization and stochastic optimization methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Mathematical optimization is used in much modern controller design.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] High-level controllers such as model predictive control (MPC) or real-time optimization (RTO) employ mathematical optimization.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] These algorithms run online and repeatedly determine values for decision variables, such as choke openings in a process plant, by iteratively solving a mathematical optimization problem including constraints and a model of the system to be controlled.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are regularly used in geophysical parameter estimation problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Given a set of geophysical measurements, e.g. seismic recordings, it is common to solve for the physical properties and geometrical shapes of the underlying rocks and fluids.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] The majority of problems in geophysics are nonlinear with both deterministic and stochastic methods being widely used.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Nonlinear optimization methods are widely used in conformational analysis.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are used in many facets of computational systems biology such as model building, optimal experimental design, metabolic engineering, and synthetic biology.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Linear programming has been applied to calculate the maximal possible yields of fermentation products, and to infer gene regulatory networks from multiple microarray datasets as well as transcriptional regulatory networks from high-throughput data.
[src:optimization-scipy/mathematical-optimization] Nonlinear programming has been used to analyze energy metabolism and has been applied to metabolic engineering and parameter estimation in biochemical pathways.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] The **Nelder–Mead method** (also **downhill simplex method**, **amoeba method**, or **polytope method**) is a numerical method used to find a local minimum or maximum of an objective function in a multidimensional space.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] It is a direct search method (based on function comparison) and is often applied to nonlinear optimization problems for which derivatives may not be known.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] However, the Nelder–Mead technique is a heuristic search method that can converge to non-stationary points on problems that can be solved by alternative methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] The Nelder–Mead technique was proposed by John Nelder and Roger Mead in 1965, as a development of the method of Spendley et al.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] The method uses the concept of a simplex, which is a special polytope of *n* + 1 vertices in *n* dimensions.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Examples of simplices include a line segment in one-dimensional space, a triangle in two-dimensional space, a tetrahedron in three-dimensional space, and so forth.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] The method approximates a local optimum of a problem with *n* variables when the objective function varies smoothly and is unimodal.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Typical implementations minimize functions, and we maximize $f(\mathbf {x} )$ by minimizing $-f(\mathbf {x} )$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] For example, a suspension bridge engineer has to choose how thick each strut, cable, and pier must be.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] These elements are interdependent, but it is not easy to visualize the impact of changing any specific element.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Simulation of such complicated structures is often extremely computationally expensive to run, possibly taking upwards of hours per execution.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] The Nelder–Mead method requires, in the original variant, no more than two evaluations per iteration, except for the *shrink* operation described later, which is attractive compared to some other direct-search optimization methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] However, the overall number of iterations to proposed optimum may be high.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Nelder–Mead in *n* dimensions maintains a set of *n* + 1 test points arranged as a simplex.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] It then extrapolates the behavior of the objective function measured at each test point in order to find a new test point and to replace one of the old test points with the new one, and so the technique progresses.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] The simplest approach is to replace the worst point with a point reflected through the centroid of the remaining *n* points.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] If this point is better than the best current point, then we can try stretching exponentially out along this line.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] On the other hand, if this new point isn't much better than the previous value, then we are stepping across a valley, so we shrink the simplex towards a better point.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Unlike modern optimization methods, the Nelder–Mead heuristic can converge to a non-stationary point, unless the problem satisfies stronger conditions than are necessary for modern methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Modern improvements over the Nelder–Mead heuristic have been known since 1979.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Many variations exist depending on the actual nature of the problem being solved.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] A common variant uses a constant-size, small simplex that roughly follows the gradient direction (which gives steepest descent).
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Visualize a small triangle on an elevation map flip-flopping its way down a valley to a local bottom.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] This method is also known as the **flexible polyhedron method**.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] This, however, tends to perform poorly against the method described in this article because it makes small, unnecessary steps in areas of little interest.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] We are trying to minimize the function $f(\mathbf {x} )$ , where $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Our current test points are $\mathbf {x} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {x} _{n+1}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Calculate $\mathbf {x} _{o}$ , the centroid of all points except $\mathbf {x} _{n+1}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] If the reflected point is better than the second worst, but not better than the best, i.e. $f(\mathbf {x} _{1})\leq f(\mathbf {x} _{r})<f(\mathbf {x} _{n})$ , then obtain a new simplex by replacing the worst point $\mathbf {x} _{n+1}$ with the reflected point $\mathbf {x} _{r}$ , and go to step 1.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] **Expansion** If the reflected point is the best point so far, $f(\mathbf {x} _{r})<f(\mathbf {x} _{1})$ , then compute the expanded point $\mathbf {x} _{e}=\mathbf {x} _{o}+\gamma (\mathbf {x} _{r}-\mathbf {x} _{o})$ with $\gamma >1$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] **Contraction** Here it is certain that $f(\mathbf {x} _{r})\geq f(\mathbf {x} _{n})$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] For the **reflection**, since $\mathbf {x} _{n+1}$ is the vertex with the higher associated value among the vertices, we can expect to find a lower value at the reflection of $\mathbf {x} _{n+1}$ in the opposite face formed by all vertices $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ except $\mathbf {x} _{n+1}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] For the **expansion**, if the reflection point $\mathbf {x} _{r}$ is the new minimum along the vertices, we can expect to find interesting values along the direction from $\mathbf {x} _{o}$ to $\mathbf {x} _{r}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Concerning the **contraction**, if $f(\mathbf {x} _{r})>f(\mathbf {x} _{n})$ , we can expect that a better value will be inside the simplex formed by all the vertices $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Finally, the **shrink** handles the rare case that contracting away from the largest point increases f , something that cannot happen sufficiently close to a non-singular minimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] In that case we contract towards the lowest point in the expectation of finding a simpler landscape.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] However, Nash notes that finite-precision arithmetic can sometimes fail to actually shrink the simplex, and implemented a check that the size is actually reduced.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Indeed, a too small initial simplex can lead to a local search, consequently the NM can get more easily stuck.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] So this simplex should depend on the nature of the problem.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] However, the original article suggested a simplex where an initial point is given as $\mathbf {x} _{1}$ , with the others generated with a fixed step along each dimension in turn.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Thus the method is sensitive to scaling of the variables that make up $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Criteria are needed to break the iterative cycle.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Nelder and Mead used the sample standard deviation of the function values of the current simplex.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] If these fall below some tolerance, then the cycle is stopped and the lowest point in the simplex returned as a proposed optimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Note that a very "flat" function may have almost equal function values over a large domain, so that the solution will be sensitive to the tolerance.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Nash adds the test for shrinkage as another termination criterion.
[src:optimization-scipy/nelder-mead-method] Note that programs terminate, while iterations may converge.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] In calculus, **Newton's method** (also called **Newton–Raphson**) is an iterative method for finding the roots of a differentiable function f , which are solutions to the equation $f(x)=0$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] However, to optimize a twice-differentiable f , our goal is to find the roots of $f'$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] We can therefore use Newton's method on its derivative $f'$ to find solutions to $f'(x)=0$ , also known as the critical points of f .
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] These solutions may be minima, maxima, or saddle points; see section "Several variables" in Critical point (mathematics) and also section "Geometric interpretation" in this article.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] This is relevant in optimization, which aims to find (global) minima of the function f .
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] The central problem of optimization is minimization of functions.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] Let us first consider the case of univariate functions, i.e., functions of a single real variable.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] We will later consider the more general and more practically useful multivariate case.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] Newton's method attempts to solve this problem by constructing a sequence $\{x_{k}\}$ from an initial guess (starting point) $x_{0}\in \mathbb {R}$ that converges towards a minimizer $x_{*}$ of f by using a sequence of second-order Taylor approximations of f around the iterates.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] The next iterate $x_{k+1}$ is defined so as to minimize this quadratic approximation in t , and setting $x_{k+1}=x_{k}+t$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] If the second derivative is positive, the quadratic approximation is a convex function of t , and its minimum can be found by setting the derivative to zero.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] Note that if f happens to *be* a quadratic function, then the exact extremum is found in one step.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] This is often done to ensure that the Wolfe conditions, or much simpler and efficient Armijo's condition, are satisfied at each step of the method.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] For step sizes other than 1, the method is often referred to as the relaxed or damped Newton's method.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] If *f* is a strongly convex function with Lipschitz Hessian, then provided that $x_{0}$ is close enough to $x_{*}=\arg \min f(x)$ , the sequence $x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},\dots$ generated by Newton's method will converge to the (necessarily unique) minimizer $x_{*}$ of f quadratically fast.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] Finding the inverse of the Hessian in high dimensions to compute the Newton direction $h=-(f''(x_{k}))^{-1}f'(x_{k})$ can be an expensive operation.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] which may be solved by various factorizations or approximately (but to great accuracy) using iterative methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] Many of these methods are only applicable to certain types of equations, for example the Cholesky factorization and conjugate gradient will only work if $f''(x_{k})$ is a positive definite matrix.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] While this may seem like a limitation, it is often a useful indicator of something gone wrong; for example if a minimization problem is being approached and $f''(x_{k})$ is not positive definite, then the iterations are converging to a saddle point and not a minimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] There also exist various quasi-Newton methods, where an approximation for the Hessian (or its inverse directly) is built up from changes in the gradient.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] If the Hessian is close to a non-invertible matrix, the inverted Hessian can be numerically unstable and the solution may diverge.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] In this case, certain workarounds have been tried in the past, which have varied success with certain problems.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] One can, for example, modify the Hessian by adding a correction matrix $B_{k}$ so as to make $f''(x_{k})+B_{k}$ positive definite.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] One approach is to diagonalize the Hessian and choose $B_{k}$ so that $f''(x_{k})+B_{k}$ has the same eigenvectors as the Hessian, but with each negative eigenvalue replaced by $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] An approach exploited in the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm (which uses an approximate Hessian) is to add a scaled identity matrix to the Hessian, $\mu I$ , with the scale adjusted at every iteration as needed.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] For large $\mu$ and small Hessian, the iterations will behave like gradient descent with step size $1/\mu$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] This results in slower but more reliable convergence where the Hessian doesn't provide useful information.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] It may not converge at all, but can enter a cycle having more than 1 point.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] See § Computing the Newtonian direction.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] It can converge to a saddle point instead of to a local minimum, as per § Geometric interpretation.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] For example, it is usually required that the cost function is (strongly) convex and the Hessian is globally bounded or Lipschitz continuous, for example this is mentioned in the section "Convergence" in this article.
[src:optimization-scipy/newton-s-method-in-optimization] One can compare with a backtracking line search on gradient descent, which has good theoretical guarantee under more general assumptions, and can be implemented and works well in practical large scale problems such as deep neural networks.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] SQP methods solve a sequence of optimization subproblems, each of which optimizes a quadratic model of the objective subject to a linearization of the constraints.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] If the problem is unconstrained, then the method reduces to Newton's method for finding a point where the gradient of the objective vanishes.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] If the problem has only equality constraints, then the method is equivalent to applying Newton's method to the first-order optimality conditions, or Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions, of the problem.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] where $\lambda$ and $\sigma$ are Lagrange multipliers.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] If the problem does not have inequality constraints (that is, $m_{I}=0$ ), the first-order optimality conditions (aka KKT conditions) $\nabla {\mathcal {L}}(x,\sigma )=0$ are a set of nonlinear equations that may be iteratively solved with Newton's Method.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] where $\nabla _{xx}^{2}{\mathcal {L}}(x_{k},\sigma _{k})$ denotes the Hessian matrix of the Lagrangian, and $d_{x}$ and $d_{\sigma }$ are the primal and dual displacements, respectively.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] Note that the Lagrangian Hessian is not explicitly inverted and a linear system is solved instead.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] When the Lagrangian Hessian $\nabla ^{2}{\mathcal {L}}(x_{k},\sigma _{k})$ is not positive definite, the Newton step may not exist or it may characterize a stationary point that is not a local minimum (but rather, a local maximum or a saddle point).
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] In this case, the Lagrangian Hessian must be regularized, for example one can add a multiple of the identity to it such that the resulting matrix is positive definite.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] The optimality conditions of this quadratic problem correspond to the linearized KKT conditions of the original problem.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] Note that the term $f(x_{k})$ in the expression above may be left out, since it is constant under the $\min \limits _{d}$ operator.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] The SQP algorithm starts from the initial iterate $(x_{0},\lambda _{0},\sigma _{0})$ .
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] This process is repeated for $k=0,1,2,\ldots$ until some convergence criterion is satisfied.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] Practical implementations of the SQP algorithm are significantly more complex than its basic version above.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] These strategies can be combined in numerous ways, resulting in a diverse range of SQP methods.
[src:optimization-scipy/sequential-quadratic-programming] SQP methods have been implemented in well known numerical environments such as MATLAB and GNU Octave.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] In mathematical optimization, a **trust region** is the subset of the region of the objective function that is approximated using a model function (often a quadratic).
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] If an adequate model of the objective function is found within the trust region, then the region is expanded; conversely, if the approximation is poor, then the region is contracted.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] The fit is evaluated by comparing the ratio of expected improvement from the model approximation with the actual improvement observed in the objective function.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] Simple thresholding of the ratio is used as the criterion for expansion and contraction—a model function is "trusted" only in the region where it provides a reasonable approximation.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] Trust-region methods are in some sense dual to line-search methods: trust-region methods first choose a step size (the size of the trust region) and then a step direction, while line-search methods first choose a step direction and then a step size.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] The general idea behind trust region methods is known by many names; the earliest use of the term seems to be by Sorensen (1982).
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] A popular textbook by Fletcher (1980) calls these algorithms **restricted-step methods**.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] Additionally, in an early foundational work on the method, Goldfeld, Quandt, and Trotter (1966) refer to it as **quadratic hill-climbing**.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] Conceptually, in the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm, the objective function is iteratively approximated by a quadratic surface, then using a linear solver, the estimate is updated.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] This alone may not converge nicely if the initial guess is too far from the optimum.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] For this reason, the algorithm instead restricts each step, preventing it from stepping "too far".
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] It operationalizes "too far" as follows.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] Rather than solving $A\,\Delta x=b$ for $\Delta x$ , it solves ${\big (}A+\lambda \operatorname {diag} (A){\big )}\,\Delta x=b$ , where $\operatorname {diag} (A)$ is the diagonal matrix with the same diagonal as *A*, and λ is a parameter that controls the trust-region size.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] Geometrically, this adds a paraboloid centered at $\Delta x=0$ to the quadratic form, resulting in a smaller step.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] The trick is to change the trust-region size (λ).
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] At each iteration, the damped quadratic fit predicts a certain reduction in the cost function, $\Delta f_{\text{pred}}$ , which we would expect to be a smaller reduction than the true reduction.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] By looking at the ratio $\Delta f_{\text{pred}}/\Delta f_{\text{actual}}$ , we can adjust the trust-region size.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] In general, we expect $\Delta f_{\text{pred}}$ to be a bit smaller than $\Delta f_{\text{actual}}$ , and so the ratio would be between, say, 0.25 and 0.5.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] If the ratio is more than 0.5, then we are damping the step too much, so expand the trust region (decrease λ) and iterate.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] If the ratio is smaller than 0.25, then the true function is diverging "too much" from the trust-region approximation, so shrink the trust region (increase λ) and try again.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] Note that the Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm does not have an explicit trust region, and is instead often referred to as a damped Gauss-Newton method.
[src:optimization-scipy/trust-region] A more fitting example of a trust region method would be Powell's dog leg method, where the update step magnitude is explicitly constrained to a trust region, c.f.
